500|$|In the Mayoral {{election}} of 1383 John Northampton lost to Nicholas Brembre, {{who was to}} hold the office for another three years. Brembre had effectively won by means of filling the Guildhall with his own – armed – supporters {{and within a few}} months Northampton was on trial for sedition (between February and August 1384), at which Exton was in attendance, again in support of Brembre. Exton was soon after elected Sheriff of London, and in 1385 was returned again as alderman. In 1386, At the October 1385 parliament, {{as a result of the}} crown's request for a <b>war</b> <b>tax,</b> it was decided to appoint two supervisors of taxation from the Lords Temporal and Lords Spiritual, to authorise all payments requested by the council. As a result, in January the following year, Exton was appointed a collector (to [...] "take, receive and keep") of the subsidy and ensure it was spent solely on military activities, and then to certify the same to the lower House. By Easter, he and his fellow collector had received some £29,000 for the tax. For these activities, Exton was paid £20 in wages, as well as a further £46 for his expenses, and additionally, free boat usage on the River Thames. Brembre came to the end of his three terms of office, and Exton was elected in his stead.|$|E
